On today’s two part podcast episode I have a conversation with a Mafia-Linked Bakery Investor,
and afterwards,
comedy genius @nickypetito. Bread For the People is streaming everywhere you get your podcasts

Join Bread For the People host Jim Serpico as he welcomes an infamous Mafioso introduced only as “Tony.” Tony is a successful entrepreneur and restaurateur who credits his own success due to his unique “management” style.. Jim expresses his surprise to be talking to Tony, stating that he had no idea the guest was still around. They have a casual conversation about Tony’s whereabouts and what he’s been up to in recent years. Tony reveals that he’s been “hiding out on the down low.” They also discuss bread preferences and Tony denies the notion that he only cares about the business model and not the quality of the bread in his investments. In the second half of this episode, Jim talks with actor, writer, and comedian Nicky Petito about what it’s like to be a working comedian, penetrating the movie business, and how Nick uses his gift and ability to mimic voices to prank people.

Follow Jim Serpico on Instagram: @sidehustlebread and @jimserpico
Follow Nicky Petito on Instagram: @nickypetito

My uncle Edmonte Salvato (Uncle D) the man responsible for half my personality and sense of humor passed away Friday. This was the last person God left my brother, sister and myself with, and he was not ready to “check out” yet as he would say. You may know him from “Carlito’s Way” with Al Pacino & other films. I saw him Monday, we were laughing and he looked as sharp as ever.  I’ve been putting off writing this as there’s been too much I want to say, and too many things that just do not add up, as I have been beyond emotionally distressed to put the words together. So I will be posting more later. For now I just want to put out the information for his services. The wake will be tomorrow at Megro funeral home in Belleville, New Jersey 4pm -8pm. Saturday from 8:30am-9:15am, & the Funeral will be Saturday at 10:00am at St Lucy’s church in Newark. Rest In Peace Uncle D, I’ll see ya up there one day with the rest of the family, & well all be listening to Mack the Knife, reunited, having a great time. 🙏
